node.text: My weight loss story summed up!

node.title: How did I lose the weight?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Mols Weightloss Transformation on July 27, 2021 tagging @getsowell. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text:
WEIGHT GAIN DUE TO HORMONES 👇🏼 And how @getsowell is about to change thousands of lives.

2.5 years ago I felt so lost and helpless with my weight and overall health. I was working my ass off in the gym, eating hardly anything (around 1100 calories) and struggling to even maintain my weight and gradually gaining. I had already lost 75+ lbs and I couldn’t for the life of me figure out what was wrong.

My symptoms included 🥴
• weight gain
• low sex drive
• acne
• trouble sleeping
• anxiety and depression

At my breaking point I found an amazing naturopath that tested all my blood work and found that I had hormonal abnormalities which were causing all these symptoms.

I know how frustrating it can be to feel like you’re doing everything right and your body's working against you. I also know that naturopaths are expensive and not always accessible to many. That’s why I’m so so so excited to have found a company that allows you to take your health into your own hands. @getsowell is a company that allows you to do blood work at home and access your results online without ever having to spend hundreds to thousands on doctors visits.

After sharing my hormone story I’ve had thousands of women ask where to start and expressed how helpless they feel. I genuinely think this company will change lives and give people a chance to really figure out what’s going on with their own bodies.

Head over to @getsowell to see the science behind why this kit could change your life!

node.text:
17 WEEKS 👀
.
There’s a bit of a bump starting to form but tbh I mostly just look bloated or like I’ve gained a weight overall in my midsection. I’ve yet to gain much weight and I’m sitting at 145 daily, I started at 148lbs dropped to 141lbs at the lowest during the first trimester while I was extremely nauseous. I cam definitely tell my bodies hanging onto more water than usual, which is A-okay. 
.
I sure don’t want to jinx it but I think this has been a pretty easy pregnancy compared to most. I rarely get nauseous anymore and I’m feeling pretty well regular day to day.
.
Now that we know the gender I’ve been going insane buying baby stuff, but I’ve been finding some great used deals! cant wait to share some of the clothes once we announce the gender!
.
There’s a little mini update for you all 💜

node.text:
Trying to stay as active as possible lately! The recent heat wave that hit BC was no joke with most days above 40 degrees, it was way too hot to leave the house.

I’m so grateful the temperature has cooled off and that masks are optional now in BC. When I first found out I was pregnant I was getting extremely lightheaded while wearing a mask and almost fainted a few times so I haven’t been in the gym in nearly 4 months. I’m so happy to get back into it and keep myself and this baby as healthy as possible!

node.text:
NOT my usual content.
.
I’m choosing to share this photo for the story and thought behind it. As I sit here pregnant, wondering how my body is about to change its hard to not be scared for the unknown. I’ve been looking at photos of myself a lot lately, wondering if I’ll recognize this body still after the pregnancy. I went most of my life in a body I was unhappy with. It’s terrifying to now think of losing everything I worked so hard for.
.
I want to embrace the changes my body is about to go through but I’m scared. I’m working towards it daily and trying to encourage myself to love and accept this body for everything it’s doing for me and my baby.
.
I just wanted to share this with you guys because even after a major weight loss and surgery there’s still a lot of emotion and feelings that can be deep rooted. I’m going to be so really an honest with you guys through this pregnancy because I think more people need to talk about the mental struggles on the route to body acceptance.

node.text:
PREGNANCY, WHAT ABOUT YOUR TUMMY TUCK!?!
.
A big question I’ve been getting and one that I’ve always thought a lot about myself.

Prior to having my tummy tuck I had spoken with my surgeon @gavindrymd @athenixbody about how I still wanted to have kids. He assured me that a tummy tuck will never effect your ability to have children or the safety of the baby, but the results of the tummy tuck could be compromised.

I’m going to share the journey with you guys and I’d be lying if I said I’m not worried about it. I definitely expect to get stretch marks over my stomach as the skin is very tight now and I’ve recently developed a lot of small stretch marks along my lower back along my scar. Ive always been very prone to stretch marks so it just is what it is. 

When looking all over for women who have had pregnancies after a tummy tuck I found almost nothing so I want to really share my experience as be candid and vulnerable with you all so you can really see what it’s all about.

Welcome to the next chapter of my life!

node.text:
When I was overweight I always felt unlovable. I felt like no one would ever be attracted to me and I was going to be alone forever.
.
Flash forward to when I lose the weight, I felt like men would initially give me attention but then I would manage to scare them off because I really didn’t know how to be in a healthy relationship, mostly because I really didn’t have a good relationship with myself, food or my body. It took my years of failed relationship and a shit ton of self work to get myself to a place where I could have a healthy relationship.
.
I just wanted to share this with you guys because weight loss and the relationship ship you have with your body has a massive role in how you feel and act in a relationship.
.
To anyone out there struggling to find yourself or the right person for you, just know that there’s someone out there for you and when you’re in the right place mentally and emotionally they’ll come out of no where!

Women have cellulite, loose skin is normal, not looking like you have a 12 year old waist is normal. Sometimes I wonder if growing up I saw more real bodies I would have had a better relationship with my own. 

This is the one body I have and I’m going to warship every inch of it. I am healthy, I’m the strongest I’ve ever been and I am so grateful especially right now for this amazing little body of mine.

node.text:
A friendly reminder, 

While some of us live for summer, some of us dread it all year. I’ve lived on both sides of the spectrum and here’s my thoughts on it. I grew up severely obese in a town where it was extremely rare (small town in Canada). The thought of putting a bathing suit on was enough to send my heart racing and face bright red.

I had cellulite and stretch marks before some of my friends even had their periods. And I’ve faced the scrutiny of my body from myself and others since before I can even remember.
.
I beg everyone to remember to firstly be kind to themselves this summer but to also be mindful of the stress and anxiety that some face as the weather heats up.
.
A strong reminder to NEVER comment on 👇🏼
• stretch marks
• hair
• cellulite
• excess skin
• weight 
• scarring 

Please be mindful of your words and even looks. Sometimes the silent stares hurt even worse. I wish that all the above listed were more so embraced and normalized (as they should be) but I also know the effect they can still have on a persons mental health. Be kind everyone (especially to yourselves) 💜

node.text:
NOT A BEFORE AND NOT AN AFTER
.
Just your daily reminder, social media is fake. I’ve been honestly so distant on social media lately because I just feel like it’s become a bit of a toxic platform. Even with posts like this, forgive me if I’m wrong but I sometimes feel like women don’t even want to be sharing photos like this but it gains them popularity. And then it’s not even authentic but a competition on who can be the most vulnerable...
.
I still love social media for connecting with people I love but I’ve definitely felt a need to step back.
.
What’s everyone’s thoughts, I’m genuinely curious?
